post_text:
#theNEISDway --Reagan cadets use virtual tools to plan for the future

Junior Reserve Officer Training Corps (JROTC) students across North East ISD have found new ways to collaborate through virtual learning. Throughout the school year, cadets often meet with military recruiters who explain the options available to students considering a future in the armed forces.

Junior and senior cadets at Reagan High School met with Sergeant Sidney Petree about the many opportunities the U.S. Marine Corps has to offer.

"Here at Reagan and across the North East Independent School District, we are quite fortunate to be supported by some of the most professional and knowledgeable military recruiters," said LTC Chad Livingston. "He is a shining example of a squared-away Marine and a great model for my cadets to emulate."

JROTC cadets across the District have been hard at work collaborating over Zoom and other digital resources to ensure their commitment to each other, and the program, remains intact. #RootEdReagan

post_text:
#NEISDcares --NEISD Board of Trustees votes to save taxpayers millions

During the Sept. 14 regular North East ISD Board of Trustees meeting, the board voted unanimously to approve the refinancing of tax refunding bonds. This is the first time in four years the District has been able to issue this sort of bond, and the hope is it will continue to save taxpayers millions.

‚Äú[Between 2012 and 2016] We refinanced $785 million worth of bonds, so we‚Äôve saved taxpayers on the backend $140 million,‚Äù explained Associate Superintendent of Business Services, Dan Villarreal. ‚ÄúWith this refunding, hopefully, we‚Äôll save another $40 million.‚Äù

‚ÄúIt just seems like a great thing to do to save our community money,‚Äù added Superintendent of Schools, Dr. Sean Maika.

In full transparency, the District‚Äôs financial advisor explained the market is in a great position to save taxpayers $40 million with this bond refunding; however the final savings tally won't be known for a few weeks.

The generosity of our community was on full display for the North East Educational Foundation‚Äôs most successful Big Give ever!

Through the support of 1,032 generous donors, NEEF raised $75,330 for NEISD campuses and programs.

The official Big Give online giving day was held on Sept. 10, but the donation page remained open through the weekend to allow for last-minute gifts to trickle in.

Funds raised will help provide updated technology for our schools, touchless water bottle refilling stations, new library books, art supplies and so much more!

A big thank you to all of our donors for being a bright spot for our campuses and teachers during this tough time! #BigGive2020

post_text: Meet Edwin, a Royal Ridge ES Pre-K student. Edwin wanted to honor this day by taking a walk with his Popo (grandfather.) His Popo is a retired Firefighter and Paramedic for the City of San Antonio. Every year, Mr. Rios walks down Crest Way and Eagle Crest starting at 7:46am Central Time when the first tower was hit. Every step after is in honor of the 2,977 lives lost on this day. This year Mr. Rios wanted to walk down Walzem Road. He walks in his full firefighter gear and carries the American flag over his shoulder. Edwin joined him on this walk with his mini firefighter gear and a little American flag over his shoulder. We will never forget and always honor the lives lost in 9/11. #NEISDcares Royal Ridge Elementary School - North East ISD

post_text:
#NEISDcares --NEISD librarian recognized by acclaimed author

NEISD librarian recognized by acclaimed author
Natalie Watts takes great pride in introducing new books to her students at Huebner Elementary School. One of her favorites is Creepy Carrots by Aaron Reynolds. The acclaimed children‚Äôs author has visited many North East ISD elementary campuses over the years, including several stops at Huebner. Reynolds and Watts bonded over their love of literature and remain friends to this day.

When Watts opened her copy of his latest book, Rescuing Mrs. Birdley, she was shocked to find her name in the dedication section.

‚ÄúI feel very honored that he recognized me in one of his latest books personally and professionally,‚Äù said Watts. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a huge shout out to librarians everywhere! It was very exciting and unexpected.‚Äù

Many of Reynolds‚Äô books are fan favorites in the Huebner library. More than anything, Watts loves being able to help her students discover new favorites. Many lifelong learners get their start at Huebner, and Watts is proud to play her part in that journey. #RootEdHuebner

#NEISDcares --Jackson-Keller ES teacher, Julie Kelly, shares a special moment she had with her student, Lilah.

"This is the first time in my 20+ years in education that I do not get to see my students in person and get those end
of the day hugs and high fives," said Kelly. "I noticed Lilah turn off her video after sharing what she learned on the second day and when she asked to talk to me after everyone left I was concerned she was struggling. To my surprise, she turned on her video and held up her sign. This touched my heart beyond words and reminds me how we touch the lives of our students no matter if it is in person or virtually."

#RootEdJacksonKeller

post_text:
NEISD Board of Trustees votes to make Election Day 2020 a District Holiday

The North East ISD Board of Trustees voted to make Tuesday, November 3, a District holiday. This declaration allows for more safety and security on our campuses during the 2020 general election, as there are 46 voting locations throughout the District. Giving students and staff this day off will help lower campus traffic and limit possible COVID-19 exposure to our NEISD community. It will also allow for more time to thoroughly clean and sanitize the areas open to voters. This District holiday is replacing the previously scheduled November 13, 2020, Battle of Flowers Holiday, which is canceled this year because of COVID-19.

The North East ISD Board of Trustees is committed to providing a safe learning environment for its more than 70,000 students, families and teachers across San Antonio. On Tuesday, July 22, NEISD board members sent a letter to Governor Greg Abbott asking for more flexibility in determining the best path to re-open our community.

‚ÄúWe are asking for more flexibility when it comes to making decisions regarding the COVID-19 pandemic,‚Äù said Shannon Grona, Board of Trustees President. ‚ÄúWe are working hard to ensure the safety of our children and staff while also ensuring they receive quality instruction. These are difficult times, but together we will navigate the challenges ahead.‚Äù

#NEISDcares ‚ÄîNorthern Hills teachers mail ‚Äòbrag cards‚Äô to students

Summer school students at Northern Hills Elementary School received a special message in the mail from their proud teachers. More than 60 ‚Äòbrag cards‚Äô were written and mailed by teachers highlighting the hard work and dedication of their distance learning students. Summer school principal Iris Escandon says this gesture is just one way teachers are staying connected with their students.

‚ÄúThe goal of our initiative was to have students know how much their teachers recognize their efforts during distance learning,‚Äù said Escandon. ‚ÄúWe recognize the teacher brags in our morning announcements, but we wanted our students and families to know that their hard work and persistence haven‚Äôt gone unnoticed.‚Äù

As online learning continues through the June semester of summer school, NEISD teachers are committed to their mission of nurturing relationships with their students despite the distance between them.

#NEISDcares --NEISD summer meal program expands with USDA donation

The North East ISD School Nutrition Services team continued its mission to serve families and students with a donation from the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA). NEISD received 3,000 boxes of donated chicken as part of the Farmers to Families Food Box Program. Families picking up curbside meals received a family-sized box of chicken from ES Foods that includes a variety of options, including chicken strips, rotisserie chicken, chicken taco filling and more.

NEISD is committed to providing its students, family and community with the resources they need for healthy meals.

For more information on North East ISD summer meals, visit www.neisd.net/Page/273 or call 210-356-9100.

For additional summer meal locations, please dial 211, or call 877-TEX-MEAL (877-839-6325).

#NEISD2020 --Senior Spotlight: MacArthur‚Äôs Brandon Groff

MacArthur High School graduate Brandon Groff has set his sights on the sky. He‚Äôs one of four seniors in the San Antonio area to earn the Daedalian Foundation Flight scholarship. Groff will spend his summer at the New Braunfels Airport where he‚Äôll take part in the Daedalian Flight Training Program. After weeks of practice, he will eventually fly solo and earn a private pilot certificate.

The Daedalian Foundation is the philanthropic arm of the Order of Daedalians. This organization aims to inspire and provide opportunities for young Americans to pursue careers as military aviators.

Groff graduated from MacArthur Summa Cum Laude and was an active member of the JROTC program, MacTEACH, PTSD Ambassadors and PALS. He earned a three-year Army ROTC scholarship and plans to join the Corps of Cadets at Texas A&M University. After graduation, Groff will commission as a Second Lieutenant in the Army.

Congratulations Brandon! #RootEdMacArthur

Start the registration process at North East ISD with the click of a button. Register your child online today by visiting neisd.net/registration. NEISD will begin processing applications on July 13. Parents can expect a phone call regarding registration after that date.

The list of documents you will need in order to register your child online include:

- Certified copy of your child‚Äôs birth certificate (copies from the hospital will not work)

- Social security card of the child being registered

- Parent or Guardian‚Äôs valid driver‚Äôs license/ID

- Proof of residency (no subleasing or room rentals permitted)

- Withdrawal from a previous school, if available

- Current immunization records

Parents can photograph those documents and upload them. If you do not have access to a computer, please visit NEISD's Community Learning Center (CLC) for assistance at 8750 Tesoro Dr. Call 210-407-0201 to reserve your spot today.

If your student is currently enrolled and attending an NEISD school, you do not need to use the online registration system.

#theNEISDway --Bradley librarian honored with Whatateacher Award

Regan Sanchez calls the Bradley Middle School library home. She‚Äôs beloved on campus for her love of books, commitment to her students, and creative, interactive activities. This all contributed to a special recognition. On Thursday, May 28, Sanchez was surprised with the Whatateacher Award after submitting a lesson plan that caught Whataburger attention.

Sanchez created a lesson called ‚ÄúWhat-a-Me,‚Äô that led students in an interactive experience helping them identify their negative thinking and ‚Äúsplatting‚Äù it away so they could focus on positive character traits. They also used an interactive sketching app to create a positive visualization of their best traits.

As part of her prize, Sanchez received Whataburger for a year, as well as a basket full of Whataburger swag. Sanchez is also proud to be Bradley‚Äôs Trinity Prize campus nominee. Congratulations Regan! #RootEdBradley

Photographer Gregg Segal inspired the virtual learning portraits project. His photo series, ‚ÄúDaily Bread‚Äù, shows what kids around the world eat over the course of one week in pictures.

"Receiving a video from Chris Cassidy at the ISS was amazing," said Frieda Farias. "I have had to miss out on a lot of senior year events and celebrations, so the video truly meant a lot to me. NEISD has done so much to prepare me for my future in computer science. In particular, my magnet program, The Engineering and Technologies Academy at Roosevelt High School, has provided me with many amazing opportunities and experiences. Most importantly, I feel as though I have made lifelong friends here."

Frieda is excited to share that she plans to attend Columbia University this fall.

#NEISDcares --SA Food Bank partners with NEISD to serve community

Hundreds of North East ISD families have extra food in their pantry thanks to a partnership between the District and the San Antonio Food Bank. Produce Distribution days will take place every Wednesday in May, with NEISD Family Specialists and volunteers from the U.S. National Guard placing food directly into vehicles.

On Wednesday, May 6, a total of 1,800 NEISD families lined up to receive assistance. Distribution locations include LEE and Roosevelt high schools, Harris Middle School and Blossom Athletic Center. Produce Distribution at NEISD sites for the month of May is currently at capacity.

If you have questions or need additional information, please contact NEISD Family Engagement at 210-407-0118.

Thank You NEISD Teachers: You inspire us! TAG a teacher that inspires YOU!

The COVID-19 health crisis has given many of us a new appreciation for the passion, dedication and love that teachers show their students every day. Now, more than ever, North East ISD is thankful for the way our teachers have been a steady, reliable presence for students in and out of the classroom.

While campuses are closed, the classrooms are not. NEISD teachers are adjusting lessons and coursework to distance learning in a matter of days and have been there to help and support their students and parents every step of the way. They‚Äôve done all of this while supporting their own families, and are only a Zoom call, phone call or email away.

Teacher Appreciation Week, May 4-8, is the perfect time to show the teachers in your life that you are grateful for their commitment and sacrifice. Thank you to the NEISD teachers who make a difference and show how #NEISDcares all year long.

#NEISDcares --National Principal Appreciation Day

Today, we pay special tribute to individuals that our schools could not run successfully without ‚Äì our principals.

Leading a school of dozens of employees and hundreds of students is an immense job that requires long hours and many skills. Now, put yourself in a principal‚Äôs shoes during the COVID-19 health crisis.

School closures, canceled events, distance learning and parent concerns were things they never could have envisioned at the beginning of the school year. But they have handled each issue with professionalism, creativity and compassion.

While we are grateful every day for these amazing men and women, we pay special tribute to them on National Principal Appreciation Day.

Join us in saying thank you to them for all they do.

post_text:
#NEISDcares --Madison student's handiwork extends across the country

Madison High School junior Sabrina Sanchez is as busy as ever. Between completing her schoolwork online and everything else that life has thrown at her over the past month, she‚Äôs still making time to give back. Sanchez started sewing facemasks complete with pockets for filters and adjustable nose pieces. So far, she‚Äôs stitched together more than 80 masks, and she has no plans to slow down. Twenty-six of the facemasks have been gifted to people in need, including those who couldn't afford one, as well as cancer and dialysis patients.

Each mask takes her roughly one hour to complete before they are shipped out or delivered to San Antonio residents or people in need across the country. Sanchez‚Äôs facemasks are currently making a difference in 11 states, in addition to Italy.

Thank you for showing how #NEISDcares Sabrina!

post_text:
Starting Monday, April 13, North East ISD will adjust its meal distribution services to Mondays and Thursdays from 11:30 a.m. ‚Äì 1:30 p.m. at the same campus locations. This change is an effort to reduce exposure for our employees and community members by limiting daily contact. While the serving days have been altered, the number of meals available for students will remain the same.

Monday meal packages will contain meals for Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. Thursday meal packages will contain meals for Thursday and Friday.

Some of the meals intended to be eaten later will be distributed frozen, and families will need to heat/thaw them when ready to eat. Food safety instructions in English and Spanish will be included.

NEISD‚Äôs Fresh Express bus program will also follow the new Monday/Thursday schedule.

For a list of NEISD Fresh Express bus stops and delivery times, curbside locations and a look at this week's menu, visit https://www.neisd.net/Page/294

post_text:
Denny Brown, Roosevelt HS Class of 2005 is a shining example of #NEISDcares!

"I have ordered groceries for my mom, who lives in San Antonio, through the Walmart and HEB pick up apps," said Virginia resident, Debra Mota. "However yesterday she went to Walmart early in the morning to grab a few necessities. She texted me a picture of this man and told me that he was standing in line and told her he wanted to buy her groceries and then he would also buy the lady's groceries that was behind her. He even told my mom if she wanted to go get more groceries, he would stand there and wait for her and pay. She said it was okay that that was all she needed, but she was so grateful to him and thanked him. She had happy tears when she left the store. Yes, there are good people out there doing wonderful things for strangers. We don't know who this man was, but I also want to thank him.

**Update** thanks to everyone who shared this, we found this awesome man. His name is Denny Brown. Sending him high fives & blessings from Virginia."

#NEISDcares --Effective April 1, parents may pick up meals without their children present at any North East ISD feeding site. Parents must provide one of the following types of documentation when picking up a meal without the child present:

Child's birth certificate (born 2001-present)
Student report card (does not have to be NEISD)
Student ID card (does not have to be NEISD)

Curbside meals are intended to be picked up for your own family, not for others. The documentation can be held up to the window for staff to inspect. There must be one piece of documentation for each child not present to receive a meal and we ask that you visit only one feeding site per day.

Documentation is not required when a child is brought to the meal site.

For a list of NEISD Fresh Express bus stops and delivery times, curbside locations and a look at this week's menu, visit https://www.neisd.net/Page/294

#NEISDcares --Thank you to Ridgeview ES mom, Nicole McMenomy, and kiddos for surprising the curbside crew with flowers, sweets, and goodies!

"We want to show our appreciation to the amazing lunch crew at Ridgeview because they are so selfless in a time when we are being told to be "selfish." They work tirelessly to provide not only meals but also a sense of normalcy for countless children throughout NEISD during a time that is confusing and scary for many people. As a parent, one of the worst feelings in the world is not being certain where or when your child's next meal is coming. But pulling up and seeing their smiling faces lifts our children up, and they know right then that everything is ok no matter how crazy the world may seem! So we and I'm sure many other children and parents would love to say a huge THANK YOU to all lunch crews, delivery crews, not only at Ridgeview but all over NEISD. Thank you so much!!" -Nicole McMenomy

#NEISDcares ‚ÄîLike so many North East ISD families, the coronavirus pandemic has turned life upside down for Amber Rockwell. The switch to online learning has been even more complicated for her children after a house fire displaced the family over spring break.

Rockwell says a difficult time for her family has been made a little easier thanks to the kindness of teachers at Hardy Oak Elementary School, Lopez Middle School and Reagan High School.

‚ÄúA family of seven stuck in a hotel room with only two Chromebooks was NOT the ideal situation for starting our online learning experience - especially with mom and dad needing to work remotely. However, our fabulous NEISD teachers kept us well-informed, organized, and confident that anything is possible. Our children especially love to meet with their teachers and classmates via video chat. It has been a blessing at a difficult time. Thank you!‚Äù

Thank you for telling your story, Amber Rockwell! We invite you to share your stories from home at neisd.net/tellyourstory.

Former NEISD student and The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill football player makes a surprise return to his 4th grade teacher, Nancy Whitehead, at Wilderness Oak Elementary!

During the month of October, before the UNC rivalry football game against Duke, Mack Brown, head football coach at UNC, told the football players that they needed to think of someone special to them that has been influential in their lives who had gone through breast cancer treatment. Mason submitted the name of his 4th grade teacher from Wilderness Oak Elementary, Nancy Whitehead. If the team won, they would get game balls personalized with the person‚Äôs name on it to give to them! UNC won on the last play of the game so Mason has a UNC victory football to give to his 4th grade teacher. Before Spring Break he returned to Wilderness Oak to surprise Mrs. Whitehead with the game ball.

‚ÄúIt is great to recognize and give back to someone who invested so much in me at an early age,‚Äù said Mason Laurence. ‚ÄùI wouldn‚Äôt be where I am today without her influence.‚Äù #theNEISDway

Harris teacher named H-E-B Excellence in Education Award finalist #theNEISDway!

Harris Middle School teacher Dottie Griffith didn‚Äôt know what to expect when a mysterious knock on the door interrupted her lesson on Wednesday, March 4. The social studies teacher with more than 20 years of experience under her belt was shocked to learn she had been named as a finalist for the H-E-B Excellence in Education Award. H-E-B representatives surprised Griffith with a $1,000 check and additional funds to be used at her home campus.

She is one of 40 teacher and principal finalists from across the state who will compete in May for top Excellence in Education honors and prizes.

Griffith is beloved on campus for her dedication to her students and her knack for incorporating song lyrics and music into her lessons. Congratulations Dottie!

Thousands of books will soon fill Blossom Athletic Center‚Äôs Littleton Gym for the 18th annual Used Book Sale.

The book sale is organized by the NEISD Council of PTAs and proceeds benefit NEISD students through projects like the Blossom Scholarship Fund, Arts in Education, Health Education Awareness, Alcohol and Drug Education, Project Graduations and Bike Rodeos.

On Friday, March 20, and Saturday, March 21, more than 90,000 books in over 25 categories will be up for grabs this year at low prices. Paperback books will be listed at 50 cents each, while hardcover books will be $1. DVDs and CDs will also be available for purchase at $1 each.

Sunday, March 22, is Bag Day, where a bag can be purchased for $15 and stuffed with all the books that can fit. Additional bags can be purchased for $10 each. Admission is free, and cash and Mastercard or Visa will be accepted. #theNEISDway

Mayor‚Äôs Cyber Cup: NEISD teams earn multiple awards #theNEISDway!

North East ISD is home to some of the best CyberPatriot teams in the nation. Teams from the Engineering Technology Academy (ETA) at Roosevelt High School, Madison High School and Krueger School of Applied Technologies (KSAT) were recognized at the 2020 San Antonio Mayor‚Äôs Cyber Cup Luncheon on Saturday, Feb. 29.

In the high school division, Madison‚Äôs Army JROTC team was awarded the Best Rookie Team, Roosevelt‚Äôs all-girl team won the Best Female Team and Roosevelt‚Äôs All-Service teams took first and second place, winning the Mayor‚Äôs Cup. Both Roosevelt teams will compete in the CyberPatriot National Finals Competition in Bethesda, Maryland March 19-23. Each team member also received a $1,000 scholarship and Microsoft Surface Pro courtesy of Northrop Grumman and Accenture Federal.

In the middle school division, the KSAT team won the Best Female Team.

Congratulations to all of the NEISD students and faculty who make our CyberPatriot programs such a success.

Spring 2020 Exam Exemption Policy Change and Guidelines

Semester exam exemptions are an opportunity for our high school students with good behavior and academic performance to exempt up to three semester exams in any subject in the spring semester. We encourage parents/guardians to keep their children at home if they are not feeling well. Hence, excused absences will not be counted against a child‚Äôs exemption. This change is only for absences between March 2, 2020, through the last day of school (May 28th) . The required semester averages are still applicable. For a child‚Äôs absence to be considered excused, students must provide a note from their parent/guardian or documentation from a doctor within 5 days of their return to school.

Unexcused absences may be considered based on the chart attached:

Join us in CONGRATULATING the new Director of North East School of the Arts, Lenida Spurlock! #theNEISDway

Lenida joined the North East family in 2015. Inspired by her own amazing teachers, she was encouraged to be a difference-maker. Before being named the Director of North East School of the Arts, she was an Assistant Principal for Reagan High School. She finds great joy in helping build capacity in students and staff to maximize and realize their own potential. Ms. Spurlock‚Äôs top priorities are children‚Äôs safety, meaningful learning, and rewarding experiences. Ms. Spurlock received a bachelor‚Äôs degree in Spanish and Dance & Theater in 1998 from Texas State University-San Marcos and earned a master‚Äôs degree in Administration in 2012 from Lamar University. Ms. Spurlock has 20 years in education.

Join us in CONGRATULATING the new principal of Hidden Forest ES, Renette Powell! #theNEISDway

Ranette joined the North East ISD family in 2016. Having lived in several countries as a military spouse, she trained and worked with individuals from different backgrounds and cultures. This fostered her passion for education and teaching. Prior to being named the Principal of Hidden Forest Elementary School, she was the Assistant Principal at Hidden Forest Elementary School. Ms. Powell received a bachelor‚Äôs degree in Criminal Justice in 2001 from Wayland Baptist University and earned a master‚Äôs degree in Business & Organizational Security Management in 2005 from Webster University. Ms. Powell wants her students to experience academic, social, emotional and physical growth and become well-rounded students. Ms. Powell has 12 years in education.

Ms. Powell wants her students to experience academic, social, emotional and physical growth and become well-rounded students. Ms. Powell has 12 years in education.

The Colonial Hills ES Student Lighthouse came up with a GREAT IDEA that benefits the entire school and community #theNEISDway!

The Student Lighthouse Team designed an outdoor library. A grandparent, Mr. George Acosta, was delighted to build it for the school.

"When my granddaughters, Olivia and Juliana, approached me to build the outdoor library I was thrilled," said George. "I knew it would inspire reading. I would do anything for my grandchildren and other children when it comes to helping with their education."

The team organized a book drive and local businesses and families donated.

"We were blessed with an abundance of books," said Colonial Hills Coach Pitts. "The outdoor library is located near picnic tables in front of the school. Many families take advantage of it. They either take the books home with them or enjoy the reading together using the picnic tables. Some families bring books to add to the library." #RootEdColonialHills

Join us in CONGRATULATING the students from the Krueger School of Applied Technologies (KSAT) who participated in the Speak Up! Speak Out! 2020 State Civics Fair sponsored by UT Moody College of Communication at the Texas Capitol.

KSAT had three teams qualify to compete at the state level. The "Insta-Investigators" team won 3rd place in the Middle School division. All three teams from Krueger/KSAT presented a problem/solution that they felt needed to be addressed in the community. The ideas were well received by the judges, and the students look forward to implementing their ideas in the coming weeks.

In addition to participating in the State Civics Fair, the students met with staff members from Senator Jose Menendez' office. They shared their project ideas with his staff and enjoyed finding out how they can make a difference in their community. Way to go! #theNEISDway #RootEdKSAT

The next FREE all city heart screenings for teenagers event will be at The College of Health Care Professionals on Saturday, February 29, 2020 and hosted by AugustHeart.

AugustHeart creates accessibility to FREE lifesaving heart screenings for teenagers to identify undetected heart abnormalities putting teens at risk for sudden cardiac death. AugustHeart heart screenings include a measure of height and weight, a modified electrocardiogram (12-lead ECG ‚Äì measures the electrical activity in the heart), and if necessary, a limited echocardiogram (2-dimensional ECHO ‚Äì ultrasound picture of the heart). Medical personnel provide an assessment of the data (normal or abnormal). All data collected related to the heart screen is reviewed by a board-certified pediatric or adult cardiologist to ensure accuracy.

To learn more about AugustHeart and free heart screenings, visit www.augustheart.org

post_text:
NEISD artists qualify for State VASE Contest #theNEISDway!

The results are in, and North East ISD is home to some of the best student artists in the state. Artwork from 100 NEISD students have advanced to the State Visual Arts Scholastic Event (VASE) contest. This is more than any other district in the region.

Of the 2,020 entries at the regional contest, 1,305 came from NEISD students. In total, 100 of the 159 regional pieces selected to move on to the state competition came from NEISD student artists. The state contest will be held on April 25 at San Marcos High School.

Art from students at Johnson, Reagan, MacArthur, Roosevelt, North East School of the Arts (NESA), International School of the Americas (ISA), Design and Technology Academy (DATA) and Engineering and Technology Academy (ETA) advanced to state.

Many of us remember taking some form of home economics in school. While the core skills have evolved over time, they‚Äôre still very much alive and well at Tejeda Middle School. Lana Harrison teaches students many of the basics in her Principles of Human Services and Principles of Hospitality and Tourism classes.

‚ÄúWhen you grow up and you enter adulthood it‚Äôs all new for you so this is kind of a way for us to practice,‚Äù said eighth-grader Zermin Khetani. ‚ÄúWhen you come in this class, you learn about stuff you‚Äôll need in the future like child development, healthy eating or cooking.‚Äù

While hands-on experiences with cooking, personal care, time management and communication are all important skills, Khetani says teachers like Harrison make her excited to come to class every day.

post_text:
2020 marks the 75th anniversary of the end of World War II and the liberation of concentration camps across Europe. Holocaust survivors have shared their stories with the world for decades, but opportunities to hear about their experience in person have become even more rare in recent years. At 92, Rose Sherman Williams is still sharing her story with students, families and community members across North East ISD and all of San Antonio.

If you‚Äôre interested in hearing Rose Sherman Williams tell her story, she will be at four more NEISD campuses in the coming months.

Madison High School: Wednesday, February 19 at 6:30 pm

Churchill High School: Tuesday, February 25 at 7:00 pm

Bradley Middle School: Thursday, March 5 at 6:00 pm

MacArthur High School: Monday, March 16 at 6:30 pm **This is an updated date and time**

NEISD student art headed to State Capitol #theNEISDway!

Five North East ISD students will have their artwork on display at the Texas State Capitol for thousands to enjoy. The exhibition is part of the Texas Art Education Association‚Äôs (TAEA) Youth Art Month celebration in March. The showcase features art from Pre-K ‚Äì 12th-grade students across the state. Only two districts in Texas had artwork from five or more students accepted, and NEISD is one of them.

The students representing NEISD include:

Rachel Kamata, International School of the Americas (ISA)
My Le, MacArthur High School
Daniel Ongmanchi, Johnson High School
McKenna Tuveson, Reagan High School
Isabella Vincenzes, Reagan High School

The artwork will be on display at the state Capitol‚Äôs Lower Rotunda from March 1-7 before moving to the Bob Bullock Texas State History Museum from March 8-28. TAEA will honor the students and their teachers at a celebration and reception on Sunday, March 22.

‚ÄúI am so proud of how both teams exhibited grace and poise under fire,‚Äù said Roosevelt High School JROTC coach, Maj. Jamelle Garner.

The next FREE all city heart screenings for teenagers event will be at The College of Health Care Professionals on Saturday, February 29, 2020 and hosted by AugustHeart.

AugustHeart creates accessibility to FREE lifesaving heart screenings for teenagers to identify undetected heart abnormalities putting teens at risk for sudden cardiac death. AugustHeart heart screenings include a measure of height and weight, a modified electrocardiogram (12-lead ECG ‚Äì measures the electrical activity in the heart), and if necessary, a limited echocardiogram (2-dimensional ECHO ‚Äì ultrasound picture of the heart). Medical personnel provide an assessment of the data (normal or abnormal). All data collected related to the heart screen is reviewed by a board-certified pediatric or adult cardiologist to ensure accuracy.

To learn more about AugustHeart and free heart screenings, visit www.augustheart.org

post_text:
DATA students at Ed White MS celebrate #BlackHistoryMonth by designing their very own telegraphs #theNEISDway!

Imagine landing a plane without the help of air traffic controllers. These controllers advise pilots on how to navigate takeoffs and landings without colliding with other planes. Granville T. Woods invented the device that allowed train dispatchers to do the same thing in 1887. Woods' invention is called the multiplex telegraph, and it allowed dispatchers and engineers at various stations to communicate with moving trains via the telegraph. Conductors could also communicate with their counterparts on other trains. Prior to 1887, train collisions were a huge problem, but Woods' device helped make train travel much safer. #RootEdDATA #RootEdEdWhite

post_text:
MacArthur students build leadership skills #theNEISDway!

MacArthur High School JROTC cadets are branching out and expanding their leadership skills through the Rotary Youth Leadership Awards (RYLA). Cadets Brandon Groff, Larissa Dretke, John Chisholm and William Allen were some of more than 150 students from around the state who took part in a retreat-style weekend that focused on leadership techniques. All of the sessions, guest speakers and activities featured hands-on, team building opportunities.

‚ÄúLast year, I walked into the camp not knowing what to expect,‚Äù said Groff. ‚ÄúI met cool people. It was a very fun experience, and it helped me get out of my comfort zone. This year, as a team leader, I had more responsibilities and it was still fun. I now have a different perspective and got to see people grow.‚Äù

Developing strong leaders is a central pillar in the JROTC program, and MacArthur is committed to empowering its students to take the lead in every aspect of their lives. #RootEdMacArthur

post_text:
NEISD is proud of our award-winning program, Meals for Shields. The program provides a free, nutritious meal to any officer who is willing to sit down and eat lunch with students.

North East ISD Chief of Police Wallace McCampbell says this program is designed to help improve community relations.

‚ÄúWe want to show the kids that the officers are their friends,‚Äù said McCampbell. ‚ÄúWe want to make them safe and we want them to be able to come to us when they have a question or a problem.‚Äù

If an officer wants to participate they must be in uniform when they check-in at the front office. After that, they will head to the cafeteria where they will enter the lunch line with the students and eat together. #theNEISDway

Longs Creek ES Music Teacher Ruth Garcia is always looking for new ways to give her students an experience like no other. So, she called the San Antonio Spurs organization to see if her All-Stars singing group, could perform the National Anthem. It turns out the National Anthem was already spoken for, so they offered her students a 90-second performance before the Anthem, and she took it.

The Longs Creek All-Stars will be performing their school song before the Spurs vs. Utah Jazz game on Jan. 29.

Garcia says the team is ready and very excited.

‚ÄúThe All-Stars are excited about singing on the basketball court and representing Longs Creek Elementary and the NEISD community! Our families are excited about the opportunity for their students!‚Äù

Again, the game is Wednesday night, Jan. 29 at the AT&T Center.

The All-Stars will be performing at about 6:30 p.m. #theNEISDway #RootEdLongsCreek

post_text:
Thank you, Sandy Winkley, for all you do to support NEISD! #SchoolBoardMonth

Sandy Winkley was elected to the board in May 2018. Sandy has held several PTA chair and officer positions at Thousand Oaks Elementary School, Bradley Middle School and Churchill High School. She served as the 50th Anniversary Liaison for Charger Sports Association. She is also a recipient of the Superintendent‚Äôs Award, the Texas Life Membership Award and Texas PTA Extended Service Award. Sandy and her husband David have two children who graduated from Churchill High School.

‚ÄúHaving raised two children in NEISD, I recognize the District‚Äôs desire to ensure that every child becomes a success, no matter what they want to do after high school," said Sandy.

The District 7 community includes: Madison High School; Bradley Middle School; and Wetmore, Northern Hills, Stahl and Fox Run elementary schools.

Join the Castle Hills Elementary School team for a special information night on Tuesday, Jan. 28, at 5:30 p.m. A tour of the school will follow a presentation and question and answer session. Information night offers parents and students the opportunity to learn more about NEISD's only year-round magnet school.

Priority enrollment is offered to the following schools: Colonial Hills, Harmony Hills, Jackson-Keller, Larkspur, Oak Meadow and Ridgeview. Roosevelt student shows off newly-discovered talent #theNEISDway!

Samuel Vasquez is a first-year painting student at Roosevelt High School. He‚Äôs always drawn pictures, but this year he decided to try something new. Art Teacher Kendra Slaughter says he‚Äôs got a knack for it, ‚ÄúHe pays attention to detail.‚Äù And it didn‚Äôt take long for her notice this painting was going to be different than the others, ‚Äúhe just did such a nice job with the symmetry of it,‚Äù adding, ‚Äúhe did a beautiful job, and I felt like it really needed to be seen by the public.‚Äù

‚ÄúI was surprised, I was like wow that‚Äôs crazy,‚Äù said Vasquez when asked how he felt about his painting being picked for a public gallery at Region 20. ‚ÄúI was just like an eye-opener for me; I was like wow, I can paint!‚Äù

The Painting II class at Roosevelt is Vasquez‚Äôs first painting class, but he says after this, he‚Äôs found a new passion and plans on taking other painting classes in the future.

His art, along with several NEISD student‚Äôs works, will be on display during February at Region 20, located at 1314 Hines Ave. #RootEdRoosevelt

His art, along with several NEISD student‚Äôs works, will be on display during February at Region 20, located at 1314 Hines Ave. #RootEdRoosevelt

NEISD is proud of our award-winning program, Meals for Shields. The program provides a free, nutritious meal to any officer who is willing to sit down and eat lunch with students.

North East ISD Chief of Police Wallace McCampbell says this program is designed to help improve community relations.

‚ÄúWe want to show the kids that the officers are their friends,‚Äù said McCampbell. ‚ÄúWe want to make them safe and we want them to be able to come to us when they have a question or a problem.‚Äù

If an officer wants to participate they must be in uniform when they check-in at the front office. After that, they will head to the cafeteria where they will enter the lunch line with the students and eat together. #theNEISDway

Thank you, Terri Williams, for all you do to support NEISD! #SchoolBoardMonth

Terri Williams was elected to the board in May 2018. Terri has lived in North East ISD for 28 years. She has served on the Bond Steering Committee, is a graduate of Leadership North East, and is a member of the NEISD Citizens‚Äô Bond Advisory Committee. She is Director of the Small Business Development Center Procurement Technical Assistance Center with the University of Texas at San Antonio (UTSA). Williams is married and has two sons who are alumni of Roosevelt High School.

‚ÄúWe will work diligently to provide the educational opportunities our children need to achieve their personal best for success academically and in life," said Terri.

The District 2 community includes: Roosevelt High School; Krueger, White and Garner middle schools; and Camelot, East Terrell Hills, Montgomery, Walzem and Wilshire elementary schools.

post_text:
Japanese exchange students experience life at LEE #theNEISDway!

The International School of the Americas (ISA) offers a unique option for students interested in experiencing different cultures. In addition to our students visiting other countries, the school often hosts students from around the world, giving them the opportunity to experience the life of an American teen. During a recent their stay, students from Takayama, Japan stopped by the JROTC facility at LEEto meet with cadets and test their skills on the air rifle range.

‚ÄúDespite the language barrier, we were able to effectively communicate and learn from one another,‚Äù said cadet Harrison Doyle. ‚ÄúOnce the safety rules of the air rifle range were explained, the Japanese students became less apprehensive to engage their targets.‚Äù

The visit was arranged by ISA internship coordinator Beth Kholmetz and instructional Dean Luke Freeman. The exchange program allows North East ISD students the opportunity to host and visit students in multiple countries across the globe.

Join us in CONGRATULATING, Elizabeth Washington, for being named the new principal of Walzem ES! #theNEISDway

Elizabeth Washington joined the North East ISD family in 2003. She credits two very special elementary teachers (Mrs. Lacy and Mrs. Pierce) for saving her as she struggled to belong in the schools as a Spanish speaker and thus became her encouragement to enter this profession. Prior to being named the Principal of Walzem Elementary, she was an Assistant Principal for Wood Middle School. Ms. Washington received a Bachelor‚Äôs Degree in Interdisciplinary Studies in 2001 from Sul Ross State University and earned a Master‚Äôs degree in Educational Administration in 2011 from Concordia University. In addition to wanting her students to feel loved and valued, Ms. Washington looks forward to building a partnership with her parents, the community and stakeholders for the well-being and learning of her students. Ms. Washington has 17 years in education. #RootEdWalzem

post_text:
ISA graduate shares first salute with former instructors
Anthony Cisneros left the International School of the Americas (ISA) behind when he graduated in 2015, but his support system on campus remains intact. Cisneros received his commission as an Army officer during a special ceremony at Texas State University, and two key members of the LEE High School JROTC program took part in the ceremony. Former Senior Army Instructor Troy Ramirez read the commissioning oath aloud, while current Army Instructor Hector Reyes shared a ‚Äòfirst salute‚Äô with Cisneros. Traditionally, the soldier who salutes the newly-pinned officer is given a decorative unit coin in appreciation.

Cisneros earned a four-year Army ROTC scholarship to Texas State University. He graduated in December of 2019 with a degree in Electrical Engineering. Next, he‚Äôll join the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers while continuing his officer training at Fort Leonard Wood in Missouri. Congratulations Anthony! #theNEISDway

post_text:
#theNEISDway --"Every moment of our lives deserves to be celebrated," said NEISD teacher, Vanessa Kerr. "When one of my student's adoption became official and his last name changed at school, I knew we had to celebrate! He had been asking his mom about when his name would be "school official " for a few weeks. I was so excited to share the news with him! We wore party hats and ate cupcakes, I printed a certificate for him, and invited my administration and other teachers in his life to join us. His smile was contagious and he told me he felt like a "king for the day". Even the smallest moment can feel like the biggest moment to someone else. Celebrate and cherish each one, big and small."

"We are very appreciative and grateful for the support we have received by everyone at Royal Ridge," said the happy student's mother, Sonia McFarlin. "God has blessed us with our children and the great support of our family, friends, and Royal Ridge Community." #RootEdRoyalRidge

post_text:
Holiday cheer filled the MacArthur library as MacArthur's MacTEACH students, and a very jolly Santa Claus, delivered gifts to ALE students.

After checking the ALE list of names to see who has been naughty or nice...and finding that they have ALL been very nice, MacTEACH students act as Santa's elves, purchasing select gifts, wrapping them, and finally turning them over to Santa for the very best of deliveries.

"It was an honor and a privilege to stop by and celebrate a little Christmas with such great kids," said Santa. "It is always great to promote how great the ALE kids are! And, a special thank you to the MacTEACH students for everything they do. They're a true inspiration."

"What is so special about this occasion is witnessing both the MacTEACH and ALE students turn into little children all over again," said Steve Davidson, MacArthur English teacher and MacTEACH coordinator. "For an hour, they are simply children sharing laughter, music, and gift-giving. I wish more students could experience moments like this."

What do gerbils, frogs, and snakes have in common? They all make science come to life in Mr. Kirkpatrick‚Äôs class! #theNEISDway #rootEdCastleHills #castlehillselementary

‚ÄúI love seeing all the animals every day. Science is fun. Teddy is my favorite. He‚Äôs so soft and nice, and I love to pet him,‚Äù says Kylie Owens.

Fifth graders get to experience hands-on science lessons daily in Mr. Kirkpatrick‚Äôs science class and having the animals is just an added bonus. Stop by the classroom anytime and students will be completing circuits, building roller coasters, or learning about the life cycle of a gerbil. Students learn about the animals and take on all responsibilities that come with caring for them. The classroom has two mice, four hamsters, two rats, five anoles, two gerbils, a toad, a leopard frog, and a corn snake. They recently- and surprisingly- welcomed eight brand new baby gerbils to their menagerie!

LEE cadets pay it forward with holiday food drive #theNEISDway!

Community service is something every JROTC cadet embraces once they commit to joining the program. Cadets at LEE High School are encouraging service during the holiday season with their most successful food drive yet. The student-organized project collected 1,436 items that will be donated to North East ISD‚Äôs McKinney-Vento Homeless Project, which includes a food pantry for students and families in need.

‚ÄúParticipating in the food drive was a great experience knowing that we contributed to our community and people in need,‚Äù said cadet Veronica Perez.

The McKinney-Vento Homelessness Project is committed to ensuring that all NEISD children and youth in homeless situations have the opportunity to attend, enroll in and succeed in school. Through this holiday food drive, cadets channeled their energy and passion into an organization that benefits their peers and community members.

To learn more about the McKinney-Vento Homeless Project, visit https://www.neisd.net/Page/657

#RootEdLEE

Through this holiday food drive, cadets channeled their energy and passion into an organization that benefits their peers and community members.

To learn more about the McKinney-Vento Homeless Project, visit https://www.neisd.net/Page/657

post_text:
The 6th Grade Krueger School of Applied Technologies (KSAT) students held its Speak Up! Speak Out! Civic Fair on December 5, 2019, at Krueger Middle School. The 6th Grade KSAT students formed 30+ teams and presented on topics from homelessness to social media issues. Hosting various business and education professionals, these judges listened to student presentations, asked probing questions, and scored the overall presentation components on a rubric. This event has qualified 16 student groups to compete on December 16, 2019, at the University of Texas at San Antonio.

Speak Up! Speak Out! is a civic education project that encourages students to become active participants in their communities. Students are responsible for determining the issues that will be addressed and for developing viable solutions that they implement. #theNEISDway #RootEdKSAT

Lopez principal Eric Wernli introduced Addie Burton, who presented the invocation, and Aidan Richard, who lead the pledges to the U.S. and Texas flags.

Addie is a key member of the Lopez basketball team who thrives on and off the court. She‚Äôs also a member of the Jr. PALS (Peer Assistance Leadership and Service), student council, the Leader in Me Lighthouse Team and the National Junior Honor Society (NJHS). Join us in congratulating students at Colonial Hills ES for helping set a new Guinness World Records Title in sport stacking!

A total of 638,503 stackers from 2,739 schools and organizations from 26 Locations/Regions came together on November 14, 2019, to break the record for the 'Most People Sport Stacking at Multiple Locations in One Day'.

Speed stacking promotes not only physical fitness but also academic learning. Students that sport stack regularly have shown increases in test scores and levels of concentration. This is achieved by students using both their right and left sides of their brain. #theNEISDway #RootEdColonialHills

The Raul Jimenez Thanksgiving Dinner provides senior citizens and less fortunate a place to enjoy a hot and nutritious turkey dinner with all the trimmings. It is a celebration and time to give thanks with peers around community dinner tables. Everyone enjoys live music and entertainment.

Thank you to the children and teachers at our elementary campuses who make this possible! #theNEISDway

Reagan HS Librarian, Christie Gudowski, shares what she DISCOVERED after a recent visit from Holocaust survivor, Rose Sherman Williams. #theNEISDway #RootEdReagan

"The audience at Reagan HS honored Rose with a standing ovation before she even began speaking! As she shared her inspiring and powerful story, the audience was captivated and reverent. Students and parents patiently waited after the speaking event to meet Rose and take photographs. Though Rose is 92 years-old and the evening ran into night time, she made every effort to stand for photos and greetings. The crowd‚Äôs response was evident that her story touched the audience, but when several students asked me the next day, if they could write their own letters to Rose, I realized how deeply they were impacted." -Christie Gudowski

‚ÄúI have a son that has been through 2 brain surgeries and plays for us," said Reagan Head Coach Hamilton. "He is a Senior on the 2019 squad. Though Drew has a limited role, he understands his place in the puzzle. He's an inspiration to me as a coach and us as a team to see how resilient he is and what he has to overcome with his five medications and implants for his condition. He may not be the best player, but I know he is better off being in football, than without it. Drew Hamilton is his name. You will not read about him in any magazine this summer for his abilities on the field but I promise, he has learned what it means to finish from what these coaches instill in his character and this team every day.‚Äù ‚Äì Coach Lyndon Hamilton

Over 300 participants had a blast dancing at the Reagan annual dance clinic. They learned routines from the Reagan JV Silver Stars and Varsity Diamond Dancers and then showed off their skills on the Reagan football field. After a little break, they took their talent to the Reagan vs. Roosevelt football game, where they performed for a crowd of thousands! #theNEISDway #RootEdReagan

Special thanks to Rolando Ordonez III for creating this incredible video! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LXm3bVadfVs&feature=youtu.be

post_text:
The Christus Mobile Clinic will provide the flu shot at no cost to students and their families from 9:00 am - 12:00 pm on Monday, Oct. 21. The mobile clinic will be located at Royal Ridge Elementary.

The clinic will offer the following:

-All vaccines required for school enrollment
-All recommended vaccines, such as HPV and Flu vaccines
-Meningococcal vaccine for students needing vaccination for entry into college

School nurses have consent/screening packets for interested families. Please call 210-954-3764 to set up an appointment.

Contact
Tamara Henderson
Email: thende5@neisd.net

post_text:
#theNEISDway --North East ISD Family Support Services hosted the Children‚Äôs Hospital of San Antonio Pediatric Mobile Clinic in support of NEISD students, families and the community. The event served 64 individuals, administered vaccines required for school enrollment, recommended vaccines, such as HPV and Flu, as well as the meningococcal vaccine for students entering college.

The two programs have collaborated for over five years and look forward to continued success in their partnership. The programs are ensuring that the North East ISD community, students and their families have access to essential medical services, comprehensive pediatric primary care, and vaccines. For more information about the Pediatric Mobile Clinic, please visit https://www.christushealth.org/santa-rosa/childrens-hospital-of-san-antonio/services-treatments/primary-care/pediatric-clinic/childrens-mobile-clinic
